1. Abstract¶

Mass shootings have one of the highest media coverage of all incidents. This issue is particarly serious in the United States. One study estimates that nearly one-third of the world's public mass shootings between 1966 and 2012 occured in the United States (Lankford 2016). We live in a society where schools, government facilities, and public institutions actively train and prepare in case of a mass shooting. Clearly, the rise in frequency and media coverage of these horrific events have left a psychological imprint.

In this analysis, we will be examining six key points: The number of shootings per year, mean fatalities per shooting, race of perpetrator, location of shooting, type of firearm used, and the mental health status of the perpetrator.

The data used has been pulled from three major sources: the Stanford Geospatial Center's Mass Shootings in America database, Everytown's Mass Shooting data, and Mother Jone's Open Source Mass Shooting database.

2.2 Fetching and Cleaning the Data¶

Since our analysis pulls from multiple sources, it's imperative to clean the data for proper integration. It is also important to note that the entries in the databases have seperate year ranges. Everytown used the years 2008 - 2019, Stanford used the years 1966 - 2016, and Mother Jones used the years 1982 - 2019. Additionally, since there is no widely accepted definition of a mass shooting, different databases record different events as a "mass shooting." For example, the Stanford Geospatial Center defines a mass shooting as 3 or more shooting victims, not including the shooter, while excluding gang, drug, and organized crime in the database. This analysis defines a mass shooting as 5 or more victims excluding gang, drug, and organized crime.

The functions below are used to tidy and standardize the data.

In [2]:
def yes_to_bool(data, col_lst):
    for col in col_lst: 
        data[col] = data[col].map({'Yes':True, 'No':False, 'N/A': False, 'Unknown': False})
def race_to_std(data, col_lst):
#     for col in col_lst:
#         data[col] = data[col].str.lower()
    for col in col_lst:
        data[col] = data[col].map({'White American or European American':'white', 'Black American or African American':'black',
                                          'Asian American':'asian', 'Native American or Alaska Native':'native american', 'Unknown':'unknown',
                                          'Unknown':'-', 'Some other race':'other', 'Unknown':'unclear'})

The sources used in this analysis have quite a bit of extraneous information, for ease of use, the columns that was not used have been dropped from the dataframes

Here, the dataframes are concatenated and is where the bulk of the tidying is done. Numbers are converted into a standard format, the dates are converted to a datetimes. It is worth noting that it is quite likely multiple sources will have duplicate events. In order to prevent double counting, it is necessary to remove duplicate entries. Detection of duplicates is done by referencing the datetime, city, state, and total fatalities. If all three match, then it is counted as a duplicate and removed.

3.2 School Related Shootings¶

In this section, only two of the three sources have information about school related mass shootings. And to account for that, one can discount the the source without school related data to prevent a skew. Panda's documentation on dropna goes in more detail: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.dropna.html

It is interesting that although the number of mass shooting increases, the number of school related shootings stays about the same. Perhaps this means that students are going through less social upheaval.

3.3 Race Analysis¶

In [14]:

Out[14]:
Text(0.5, 0, 'Race')

Doing a basic graphing of what races are commiting the mass shootings we can see that, Caucasians are doing the majority of the work. This might reinforce the image of the classic school schooter in your head. However, this does not tell the full story, seeing as the majority of the US is still white. To get a more accurate picure of what races are likely to commit mass shootings, lets try to normalize the data.

In [15]:
r_pop = pd.read_csv('QuickFacts Dec-16-2019.csv')
r_pop = r_pop.loc[8:12]
r_pop['United States'] = r_pop['United States'].str.replace(',', '')
r_pop['United States'] = r_pop['United States'].str.replace('%', '').astype('float')
r_pop.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

trim_race = ag.dropna(subset=['Race'])
trim_race = trim_race[trim_race['Race'] != 'unclear']
my_colors = list(['y', 'k', 'r', 'b', 'g'])

race_count = trim_race.groupby(ag['Race']).size()
race_count['white'] *= 1- (r_pop.iloc[0]['United States'] / 100)
race_count['black'] *= 1- (r_pop.iloc[1]['United States'] / 100)
race_count['native american'] *= 1- (r_pop.iloc[2]['United States'] / 100)
race_count['asian'] *= 1- (r_pop.iloc[3]['United States'] / 100)
race_count['other'] *= 1- (r_pop.iloc[4]['United States'] / 100)


m = race_count.plot(kind='bar', title="The Shootings per Race Normalized by Percent Populous", color=my_colors)
m.set_ylabel("Mass Shootings")
m.set_xlabel("Race")
Out[15]:
Text(0.5, 0, 'Race')

Here I took some Census data on the percentage of different races within the US. Multiplying the number of mass shootings by each race by 1 minues the percent of that race in the US gives us a normalized graph. This new graph tells quite a different story, Caucaisans are not responsible for substantially more mass shootings if we take into account the population within the us. This new graph shows us that you cannot really pin the rise in shootings to one race or poeple. It is an overall increase and shooter are most likely a product of their circumstance.

A first step in trying to combat this epidemic would be to understand why certain states are conducive to these terrible acts of violence.

4. Analysis, Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning:¶¶

First lets try the most basic form of regression, Linear Regression. To do this we will draw a line that minimizes the error between it and each point on the graph.

In [22]:
X = np.array([[y] for y in lin_tab['year']])
y = lin_tab['count']
lw=2

reg = linear_model.LinearRegression()
arr = np.array([[y] for y in lin_tab['year']])
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(X, reg.fit(X, y).predict(X), lw=lw)
ax.scatter(X,y)

ax.set_title("Number of Mass Shootings per Year")
ax.set_ylabel("Number of Mass Shootings")
ax.set_xlabel("Year")
Out[22]:
Text(0.5, 0, 'Year')

While this approach is simple and often effective, isnt a great fit for our data. The nummber of shootings has exploded in recent times, and as a result the counts are not very linear and, therefore, are not predicted well by just a line. Lets try to remedy this with polynomial regression.

In [23]:
plt.plot(X,y,'o')

poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)
poly_years = poly.fit_transform(X)
reg.fit(poly_years, y)

poly_pred = reg.predict(poly_years)
plt.plot(X,poly_pred)
Out[23]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7efbd84e4470>]

Using a degree two polynomial we can fit our data better than before, but there is still room for improvement. The jump in our data is more steep and we don't start with a dip in values. To try to get a steeper curve, lets increase the degree of the polynomial we are trying to match.

In [24]:
plt.plot(X,y,'o')

poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=3)
poly_years = poly.fit_transform(X)
reg.fit(poly_years, y)

poly_pred = reg.predict(poly_years)
plt.plot(X,poly_pred)
Out[24]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7efbd84e47f0>]

Finally using a thrid degree polynomial we get the best match for our data. This will likely be the best predictor of mass shootings going forward. While it is unlikely that this sharp spike in shootings continues, it is difficult to know when it will taper off. Again this increase in number could also be partly due to the inrease in awareness of the phenomena and more careful tracking of events. But it is unlikely that this is only cause, and the topic is still and area in desperate need of attension.

In [25]:
svr = SVR(kernel='rbf', C=100, gamma=0.05, epsilon=.1)
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(X, svr.fit(X, y).predict(X), lw=lw)
ax.scatter(X,y)

ax.set_title("Number of Mass Shootings per Year")
ax.set_ylabel("Number of Mass Shootings")
ax.set_xlabel("Year")
Out[25]:
Text(0.5, 0, 'Year')

Lastly, to get an even more acurate match for our data we used an SVR or Support Vector Regression. As you can see this form of regression creates a very close fit to the data, however, becuase it is fit so closely it is very prone to overfitting. Overfitting meaning that it is following the dataset too closely and therefore would not be a good predictor of future data. This is likely and issue here considering that our data set is not very large, so splitting it effectively for testing and iteration becomes difficult.

4. Conclusion¶

From this analysis, we can safely say that the United States is in a state of emergency. The last 15 years mark a new age of frequent mass shootings. Interestingly, the mean total victims is going down, which was contrary to our expectations. California and Texas represented most of the mass shootings, however, when adjusted for population, one can conclude that Washington, New Mexico, and Alabama are particularly bad when it comes to mass shootings.
